  - source: proto-06-complementary-no-disputes.md
    name: FAF defines. Complementary by default. No disputes in the stack.
    description: Canonical three-clause framing of FAF's architectural posture. Supersedes the "wins on conflict" framing
      — the architecture has no disputes to adjudicate, by design.
    type: feedback
    dates:
    - '2026-05-12'
    related:
    - feedback-quote-doctrine-whole-or-skip.md
    - feedback-wins-is-banned-word-in-faf.md
    - rom-defines-ram-executes.md
    body: '**Canonical three-clause phrasing — wolfejam 2026-05-12:**


      > *FAF defines. It is complementary by default. It has no disputes in the stack.*


      **Provenance:** This doctrine originated in wolfejam''s correspondence to `agent2agent@ietf.org` (the IETF Agent-to-Agent
      mailing list). Not just internal coining — it has documented IETF-list provenance, which means the IETF audience working
      on agent-to-agent protocols has already received this framing in writing. Citable as background in cover letters, sponsorship
      requests, or doctrine references; the original letter is the canonical source.


      **Why this matters:**

      - *"FAF defines"* — `.faf` is the definition layer. Not a participant, the source.

      - *"Complementary by default"* — FAF works alongside other layers (CLAUDE.md prose, README, codebase, vendor MDs); not
      in competition with them.

      - *"No disputes in the stack"* — the architecture is designed so the question "which value is authoritative?" doesn''t
      arise. `.faf` defines; everything else renders or derives. Apparent conflicts are upstream definitional gaps, not stack
      disputes.


      **How to apply:**

      - Public copy, doctrine references, technical writing about FAF behavior: use this framing.

      - For close comments / docs that touch field-level questions (e.g., "what if `.faf` and CLAUDE.md diverge?"), the answer
      is architectural — there are no disputes by design. `.faf` defines; CLAUDE.md is downstream rendering. "Divergence"
      is the wrong frame.

      - Quote the full three-clause phrase OR drop the doctrine and state behavior declaratively. Never quote a tail fragment.


      **Related:**

      - `feedback-wins-is-banned-word-in-faf.md` — surface-level word ban; this is the underlying architectural reason.

      - `feedback-quote-doctrine-whole-or-skip.md` — fragment paraphrase rule.

      - `rom-defines-ram-executes.md` — operational primitive (FAF=ROM, AI=RAM, bi-sync binds).'
